tickerjournal.urlTitle: Best Buys Now: Do More With What You've Got
tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buys 2018-3
tickerjournal.value: Heart-pump innovator Abiomed (NASDAQ: ABMD) is staying in circulation as a Best Buy for the second straight month. We were impressed with the company's fiscal third quarter, which saw not only a big jump in sales but also yet another guidance increase. We're even more excited about the company's long-term trajectory. With the Impella catheter still used in only about 9% of high-risk angioplasty procedures, Abiomed still enjoys plenty of open space to grow — wide open, because it doesn't have any significant rivals. Its near-monopoly is helping to clear the way for newer products focused on right-side heart failure, cardiogenic shock, ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI), and long-term left-ventricular assistance.

tickerjournal.name: Article in IBD
tickerjournal.value:
The first software wave was enterprise resource planning (ERP), which transformed back-office operations. Then came customer relationship management (CRM), which changed front-office operations. Adobe is calling the third wave “experience business,” which aims to reinvent how companies create, deliver and market products and services.

Adobe is the leader in digital content creation with its Creative Cloud offerings. Now it is moving aggressively into the marketing world with its Marketing Cloud, Adams said.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buy 2021-12
tickerjournal.value:
Overall, systems and services revenues increased 57.3% year over year in the third quarter, and this growth was largely driven by continued dental practitioner adoption of the iTero Element 5D Plus Series, which helps detect and monitor cavities without using radiation. The range of uses for iTero as well as growing adoption of the system could serve as a dentist's gateway into Align's ecosystem of products.

And it doesn't end there, as the company also aims to reimagine the dentist's treatment experience with end-to-end digital workflows, enabling seamless scanning, planning, treating, and monitoring of patients. Within the ecosystem of products, dentists can take digital scans of teeth through iTero, get computer-modeled digital treatment plans through Align's internally developed ClinCheck (which simulates tooth movements in stages), interact with patients through Invisalign Virtual Appointment and Invisalign Care (to check their progress), and, of course, get all those plastic aligners.

We believe that Align is more than just pieces of plastic; it's a growing ecosystem of products and, as a result, a compelling investment.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-7
tickerjournal.value:
offers an alternative to traditional braces with Invisalign, the clear-plastic, removable orthodontic aligners.

As a result, Align has a huge opportunity for growth and is seizing it with a brand-awareness campaign through YouTube videos and TV ads geared toward mothers. Align has also partnered with social media influencers (who chronicle their Invisalign journeys), the NFL, the Golden State Warriors, and U.S. Ski & Snowboard. The company credits its teen- and mom-focused marketing with driving a 138% year-over-year increase in unique visitors to the website and a 35% increase in sales leads.

Total teen and younger patients increased 58.9% year over year, and adult patients increased 68.5% year over year during the first quarter of 2021. This strength helped drive record revenues of nearly $895 million in the first quarter, which was an increase of 7.2% over last quarter and an increase of 62.4% over the COVID-impacted first quarter of 2020.

But that's hardly the end of the story. Align is expanding its presence internationally with marketing campaigns that have helped drive brand awareness and an 83.2% year-over-year increase in international Invisalign case volumes in the first quarter. The company also plans to open a new manufacturing plant in Poland to expand further into the Europe and Middle East market, a region with more than 5 million cases of malocclusion every year.

Given the company's large runway for growth and a marketing campaign that's already getting results, shares of Align might be just the thing to bring a smile to your face.

tickerjournal.name: RB Recommendation 2022-09
tickerjournal.value:
Founded in 2003, the company plugged away for a decade and a half on ways to incorporate a Nobel Prize-winning discovery called RNA interference (RNAi) into human therapeutics.

Then, in 2018, Alnylam got its first drug approved. Onpattro is the leading treatment for a disease called transthyretin-mediated amyloidosis (ATTR). Onpattro was followed by the approval of a drug called Givlaari, for a liver disease called acute hepatic porphyria, in 2019. In 2020, the company got approval for Oxlumo, which treats a rare disease called primary hyperoxaluria type 1. In 2021, Novartis (NYSE: NVS) secured approval of Leqvio, a cholesterol-lowering drug Alnylam had developed and outlicensed. The streak continued this year, too, as the company won Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approval in July for a follow-on to Onpattro called Amvuttra (more on that later). It is a streak of productivity -- and of clinical success -- pretty much unprecedented among mid-cap biotechs.

we see the company entering a new chapter that could secure its place among large-cap biopharmas with relatively muted downside risk.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buy 2016-01
tickerjournal.value:
And RNA interference specialist Alnylam Pharmaceuticals (NASDAQ: ALNY) is set to have a very exciting 2016, with a large amount of important clinical data coming down over the coming months. This may not be a year in which every biotech defies gravity, but a company like Alnylam that is steadily moving closer to multibillion-dollar opportunities will see gains ahead.

Very strong pipeline of drugs to come out.

tickerjournal.urlTitle: RB Podcast: 6 Stocks We're Watching in 2016
tickerjournal.name: RB recommendation in 2016-1
tickerjournal.value:
in 2014, the FDA approved more novel drugs (what they call "new chemical entities") than any time since 1996.
A lot of those drugs are biologics. 
I'm going to declare 2016 to be the year of RNA.

A wave of euphoria passed over Biogen (NASDAQ: BIIB) shareholders on June 7, when the FDA announced approval for Aduhelm. It's the first treatment for Alzheimer's disease approved in almost two decades, and the only drug meant to address the underlying cause of the disease, not just symptoms. The stock jumped as much as 64% that day — not something you often see with a large-cap company — before settling back to a 38% gain.

We think this is a case of missing the forest for the trees. Treatment for Alzheimer's disease is a massive unmet need, and Biogen has been given the green light for the only drug that addresses its root cause. Yes, there are other beta amyloid drugs that may now have a shot at reaching the market. Yes, there are likely to be some limits on who gets this drug. Biogen's pricing strategy — the sticker price is $56,000 annually — indicates that the company always expected this to be a targeted therapy, focused on the kinds of patients who were in the clinical trial.

tickerjournal.name: 7 best for April 2023 from Zack.
tickerjournal.value:
Salesforce (CRM) is the leading provider of on-demand Customer Relationship Management (CRM) software, which enables organizations to better manage critical operations.

The company's fiscal 2023 (2022) revenue jumped 18% (22% in constant currency) to $31.4 billion to help boost its adjusted earnings by 10%. The firm's adjusted operating margin popped from 18.7% in FY22 to 22.5% in FY23. The company also topped our Q4 FY23 estimates on March 1, with CRM beating the Zacks EPS estimates by 24%. Salesforce provided upbeat top and bottom-line guidance for the current fiscal 2024.

Current Zacks estimates call for its revenue to climb 10.5% this year to $34.6 billion and then another 11% in FY25 to $38.5 billion. Better yet, its adjusted earnings are projected to climb 33% and 26%, respectively during this same stretch. On top of that, CRM's consensus FY24 and FY25 earnings estimates have surged since its recent release.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-6
tickerjournal.value:
Investors seem to have been uncertain about salesforce.com (NYSE: CRM) ever since the company announced it was buying Slack for $27.7 billion back in December. Questions percolated about whether the company would be forced to chase growth through acquisition that it couldn't produce on its own.

The first quarter should have put that to rest. Revenue, which grew at an impressive 20% in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2021, accelerated to 23% in the company's first quarter of fiscal 2022 (ended April 30). Founder and CEO Marc Benioff called it "the best quarter we've ever had," and expects revenue to hit about $26 billion this year — especially remarkable when you consider the company achieved $10 billion for the first time in 2018.

Another milestone: The company is already the largest CRM player in the world, but Benioff noted it is about to surpass SAP (NYSE: SAP) as the world's largest enterprise software application company. David has officially slayed Goliath.

For all that, the stock still hasn't moved out of a fairly narrow range for most of the past year. We think the completion of the Slack acquisition — expected in the current quarter — and its integration into all the company's clouds, will get investors motivated again.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-5
tickerjournal.value:
Freshpet (NASDAQ: FRPT) has made the barriers even higher. Its fresh, refrigerated pet food is available in grocery stores where there simply isn't room for competitors. With branded fridges at just under 23,000 stores nationwide — including big chains like Walmart (NYSE: WMT) and Target (NYSE: TGT) — Freshpet has found itself a prime spot by the fire, and it's not moving. It's now larger than any dry dog food brand in the grocery channel, and growing faster. Indeed, the company's biggest problem right now is that it isn't able to keep up with demand, and management doesn't want to place more refrigerators in stores if it can't keep them stocked.

Luckily, Freshpet is addressing that. Earlier this month, management said it had boosted production by almost 50% from a year earlier and was working on refilling the inventory pipeline. That points to new opportunities to get the brand in significantly more locations this year.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-4
tickerjournal.value:
the pioneer of the fresh pet food category. Revenue growth has actually accelerated every year since 2016, and in 2020, it reached nearly 30%.

That's no accident. Management has been savvy in snapping up limited refrigerator space at grocery stores, making it difficult for would-be rivals to offer a similar experience. You can find the company's refrigerator cases at chains like Walmart (NYSE: WMT), Target (NYSE: TGT), and others. Freshpet ended last year at about 22,700 retailers.

At this point, many converts to Freshpet, whether two-footed or four-footed, have become habituated to the experience. Heck, even your vet will tell you to be careful about switching foods too quickly. And most owners (and, of course, pets) are highly satisfied. Freshpet set out with a goal of reaching $1 billion in sales in 2025. It recently raised that target to $1.25 billion, on the way to a larger goal "well north" of $2 billion. Either way, it's a long way from the $319 million in sales the company recorded last year.

tickerjournal.urlTitle: First Solar: Major Winner In AI Boom
tickerjournal.name: FSLR benefiting from AI boom
tickerjournal.value:
First Solar has built a strong balance sheet and dominant position in the US solar industry, while competitors struggle.
The rise of AI and LLMs has increased the demand for cheap energy generation, making solar PV an ideal solution.
First Solar's Cadmium Telluride panels are more cost-competitive and durable for utility-scale projects, giving the company an advantage.

Solar PV has now become more cost competitive than even coal and gas in an increasingly large number of areas. This makes utility-scale solar PV an ideal solution to meet the growing energy demands of AI pure plays like OpenAI and hyperscalers alike. First Solar is incredibly well-positioned to meet these growing energy demands, especially considering the fact that the company is far better capitalized than competitors in the US. 

First Solar has proven that its Cadmium Telluride panels are more cost-competitive than its crystalline silicon counterparts when it comes to utility-scale projects, specifically in the US. In fact, many crystalline silicon manufacturers in the US have gone bankrupt or are on the verge of bankruptcy. 

Cadmium Telluride solar panels have proven to be more durable, which is a big advantage when considering many utility-scale solar projects are built in deserts.

First Solar's only real competitors at the utility-scale are Chinese manufacturers, which are currently facing their own massive issues as a result of tariffs and supply gluts. 

In addition, the debate has not been settled on whether or not Cadmium Telluride will be competitive with traditional solar technologies like crystalline silicon in the long-run. Even if First Solar is able to overcome these hurdles in the near-term, the scarcity of tellurium could pose a major bottleneck to the company's growth.

tickerjournal.urlTitle: First Solar: Strong Future Ahead For US Based Solar Manufacturing
tickerjournal.name: Editor's pick from Seeking Alpha
tickerjournal.value:
the largest domestic solar manufacturer and most valuable solar company globally

large bookings backlog and focus on grid scale projects

the low levelized cost of energy ($28 to $41 per MWh) associated with grid scale solar. It should be noted that residential rooftop solar is one of the most expensive forms of generation ($147 to $221 per MWh) and the residential solar market has taken the largest hit in this down-cycle.

At the moment, the largest demand driver for their panels are large tech firms expanding their data center capacity. 

First Solar has manufacturing facilities throughout Asia and the US. They are focusing their expansion efforts in India and the US at the moment. In the US, First Solar is working on building new factories in Alabama,

Last year, 390 GW of solar generation capacity was installed globally. China meanwhile, has around 844 GW of solar production capacity, and they are expected to add another 500 to 600 GW of production capacity this year. That would put China's production capacity at 3.5x global demand.

The White House also announced tariffs on solar cells, whether they are assembled on not, would be increasing from 25% to 50% by the end of the year. 

Part of their Ohio facility is a new R&D center and production line dedicated to perovskite development. Perovskite solar cells are seen as the next generation in solar technology, leading to better efficiency and lower costs. Management expects the new facility to open during the second half of the year.

Another technology First Solar is rolling out are their CuRe modules. In CuRe panels, some of the copper is replaced with other metals, resulting in improved performance and longevity. Management expects to begin production at their Ohio facility in Q4, and they plan to convert existing production lines next year.

First Solar has a strong balance sheet with $1,990 million in cash, equivalents, and short-term investments with only $682 million in debt.

tickerjournal.name: Best Buy 2022-5
tickerjournal.value:
Slow and steady wins the race. Gartner's growth is rarely splashy, but it's refreshingly consistent. Gartner has posted double-digit revenue increases in 9 of the last 12 years, and it's at it again in 2022. Revenue rose 14% in its latest quarter, up 16% on a foreign-exchange-neutral basis.

Gartner isn't like many of our faster-growing disruptors that invest their money in tech, expansion, and the dreams of tomorrow. Gartner returns its money to shareholders. Last year, it bought back 1.6 million shares, reducing its share count by nearly 7%. The gesture is what pushed single-digit net income growth in its latest quarter into a double-digit gain on a per-share basis.

There's money to be made in taking things slow and steady. Gartner has nearly tripled -- up 183% -- since we initially recommended it six summers ago. It was a smart buy then, and it's a Best Buy Now.

With the dust starting to settle at least in terms of visibility, we find MercadoLibre continuing to dominate its markets. It has only become a more indispensable player in Latin America's booming e-commerce and fintech arenas. We think now is a good time to get in, so we're making it a Best Buy Now.

MercadoLibre is cranking out record results. Revenue rose 67% to $2.2 billion in its latest quarter, or a still-impressive 63% in U.S. dollars. The namesake e-commerce platform that initially put MercadoLibre on the map is still a beast. Gross merchandise volume increased 32% to $7.7 billion for the first three months of 2022.

And the rest of its businesses are growing even faster. MercadoPago, the peer-to-peer payment platform, saw its payment volume skyrocket 81% to $25.3 billion. Yes, the payment solution that originated on its e-commerce marketplace is now generating more than 3 times the transactions taking place on MercadoLibre.com.

There are now 81 million active unique users across MercadoLibre's offerings, 15.7% more than the 70 million it was serving a year earlier. This is a challenging climate, but MercadoLibre is doing the right thing by growing its reach and footprint. This is a high-quality international player with a long history of raising the bar through Latin America.

The stock is now down nearly 70% from its peak. We can say that about a lot of growth stocks, but it's a reminder that some drawdown bargains are higher-quality opportunities than others.

tickerjournal.name: Best Buy 2022-5
tickerjournal.value:
MercadoLibre -- with all of its various businesses pushing higher -- is one of the faster-growing names in our universe of top-notch investments.

Even after the sharp drawdown, MercadoLibre continues to be one of our scorecard's biggest long-term winners. The stock is our second-biggest gainer, a 56-bagger since we first singled it out 13 years ago. We've been believers in MercadoLibre for a long time, but we still feel we're in the early innings here. Latin America is still early in its migration online, and the middle class should only widen -- expanding MercadoLibre's addressable market -- over time. MercadoLibre is a Best Buy Now this month.

With the stock down to levels last seen in the springtime of 2020, we feel that MercadoLibre is a great buy here. The long-term upside of the Latin American region is substantial. MercadoLibre's scalability and optionality give it room to not only excel where it is now but also dive into new areas with a strong potential for success.

MercadoLibre has evolved into a giant player in several important growth markets in a region that is still somewhat early in the migration process. Less than 70% of Latin America is currently online, well below the 95% penetration rate we have in North America. When you consider a middle class that should expand over time, the addressable market that will be there for MercadoLibre to take is encouraging.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-10
tickerjournal.value:
Shares of the leading Latin American marketplace operator are trading 5% lower through Monday's close, a far cry from the double-digit gains of the major market indices. MercadoLibre's fundamentals deserve better than this year's stock chart. Revenue soared 103% to $1.7 billion on a foreign exchange–neutral basis, up a still-respectable 94% once the results are translated to U.S. dollars for Stateside investors.

A lot of companies are posting inflated financial results when pitted against pandemic-sandbagged performances during the springtime and summer of last year, but that's not MercadoLibre. Revenue skyrocketed 123% for the e-commerce speedster in the prior year's second quarter.

There is a lot to like in MercadoLibre. The stock might be marching in place this year, but the business is booming. There are 75.9 million unique active users on the platform, 47% more than over a year ago.

And it's not just the namesake marketplace that's killing it right now. Total payment volume through Mercado Pago has risen 56% over the past year in U.S. dollars (up 72% on a foreign exchange–neutral basis). Its Mercado Envios fulfillment arm has seen shipments climb 46% over the past year.

We also can't say that MercadoLibre has fallen out of favor because it's not riding hot trends. Three weeks ago, it helped roll out its first special-purpose acquisition company, or SPAC. It teamed up with Latin American venture capitalist Kaszek Ventures to launch MELI Kaszek Pioneer Corp (NASDAQ: MEKA), hoping to bankroll a promising Latin American technology company. The SPAC is already up 30% in its young publicly traded tenure.

We think the time is right to take another look at our second-best performer. MercadoLibre keeps winning mindshare in a region that is still early in its e-commerce and fintech migration. It's a Best Buy Now recommendation.

tickerjournal.urlTitle: MercadoLibre Keeps Riding Latin America's Rebound
tickerjournal.value:
Coming into Thursday's third-quarter financial report, MercadoLibre shareholders were hoping that the worst was over for the Latin American consumer market and that the company would therefore produce strong results. MercadoLibre did exactly that, and it thinks that even better times might lie ahead.

Sales soared 37%, to $230.8 million, exceeding even the optimistic 32% pace of growth that investors had been hoping to see. Net income climbed 27%, to $85 million, and that produced earnings of $0.88 per share. That was $0.05 per share higher than the consensus forecast among investors.

MercadoPago payment service has been an important contributor to MercadoLibre's overall strength. Total payment transactions grew by two-thirds, to 36.8 million, and total payment value climbed to $2.11 billion.

Shipping has also been a success for MercadoLibre. The total number of items shipped using the MercadoEnvios service climbed to 23.1 million, rising 86% from the year-ago number. Almost three-quarters of items sold in Brazil shipped using the service, and rising percentages in Mexico, Argentina, and Colombia are also using MercadoEnvios.

About 7.7 million new confirmed registered users came on board during the quarter, pushing the total number to 159.3 million. That's up 15% from where it was a year ago, and it continues to make all of MercadoLibre's businesses more valuable.

MercadoLibre  (NASDAQ: MELI) has been heading south since May, and we don't mean further into South America. But we think that just makes for a better long-term opportunity. The company continues to face strong currency headwinds, particularly in Venezuela, yet it is moving more volume through its platform; converting more shoppers to its payment system, MercadoPago; and shipping more items through MercadoEnvios. The company is seriously out of favor  right now, and we don't know exactly when that will change. But under the leadership of Marcos Galperin — who owns 9.6% of the company through a trust — MercadoLibre is building a vertically integrated ecosystem very reminiscent of Amazon.com  (NASDAQ: AMZN). MercadoLibre's part of the world poses its challenges, but we like its $4.1 billion market cap and increasingly entrenched position in Latin American commerce.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-9
tickerjournal.value:
Moderna expects to earn revenue of $20 billion from COVID-19 vaccine sales in 2021. With this figure in the denominator, the price-to-sales ratio is 8.4 (Moderna's market cap at time of writing is about $169 billion). This seems like a reasonable price to pay for a company with Moderna's prospects.

Only about 42% of the world's population has received one dose of a COVID vaccine, so the percentage of people fully vaccinated is lower than that. Considering this gap and the booster shots that will probably be widely delivered, Moderna can still expect a few years of good vaccine sales. For 2022, it already has advance purchase agreements in place to supply $12 billion of vaccine, with an optional additional $8 billion. The company can use this money to advance the other exciting drug candidates and modalities in its pipeline. ("Modality" means a new way of applying its core mRNA expertise.)

Moderna has eight other vaccines in various stages of the trial process. There is presently no vaccine for many of the illnesses under study, such as for RSV, CMV, HIV, and Zika. On Aug. 3, 2021, the RSV vaccine candidate received fast-track designation from the FDA because it is promising and meets a high, currently unmet need. Moderna also has a seasonal flu vaccine in the pipeline.

In the longer term, the company's plan is to offer vaccines that immunize against multiple viruses in a single dose. This is much easier to do with an mRNA-based vaccine compared to one that relies on a deactivated virus.

Vaccines are necessary and generate reasonably predictable revenue but are not that exciting. The exciting part about Moderna is when we ask the question: If we can harness the human body to manufacture the medicines it needs, what are the possibilities? If we just focus on writing the code and let our bodies provide the machinery, what can we do?

One of the applications of mRNA technology is in generating secreted proteins. mRNA vaccines cause an antigen to be presented on the surface of the cell, which the body's immune system then generates antibodies for. Moderna has a molecule in phase 1, mRNA-1944, that actually causes ready-made antibodies to be secreted from cells. Specifically, this mRNA causes the secretion of antibodies that kill the chikungunya virus. Moderna was the first company to produce this effect in humans using mRNA.

Vaccines and secreted proteins are Moderna's core modalities. This means the company is focusing its attention and capital on advancing therapeutics in this area. But it is also pushing along the "exploratory" modalities. These include:

mRNA cancer vaccines. This involves injecting mRNA into the body that results in the production of neoantigens, molecules that identify a tumor cell. These elicit an immune response, which enhances the body's ability to kill actual tumor cells, thus potentially treating cancer.
mRNA localized regenerative therapeutics. This involves using mRNA to get cells at a particular site of the body to produce proteins that provide a therapeutic effect in the targeted tissue.
mRNA systemic intracellular therapeutics. This involves using mRNA to create proteins that stay within the cells, meaning they are not secreted. Many genetic diseases result from a malfunctioning gene that doesn't produce a required protein, so this could be a solution to that problem.
It has only been slightly more than one and a half years since the first mRNA-based medicine was approved. It functions at the most fundamental level of biology. Understanding and being able to apply this knowledge gives Moderna huge optionality. And with vaccine sales, money is far less of a constraint than it used to be. Moderna currently has $8 billion in the bank to fund this R&D and plenty more coming in. In the next five years, a lot could go right for this company, and for this reason, we're recommending it as a Best Buy Now.

I'm expecting ResMed to grow both earnings and free cash flow about 10% to 12% annually over the next several years. It is in the sweet spot of its evolution toward becoming a major biopharma company. 

Vertex is nearly synonymous with the treatment of cystic fibrosis, a heritable genetic disorder that leaves the lungs unable to clear away sticky mucous.

Trikafta is now responsible for the vast majority of Vertex's revenue (86% of product sales in the most recent quarter) as patients switch away from older drugs. 

Luckily, Vertex has used its cash to make some fairly bold investments in its pipeline, and several of those programs are getting close to market. One you might have heard of comes from the company's partnership with CRISPR Therapeutics (NASDAQ: CRSP). 

On top of this, the company is advancing a nonopioid pain drug called VX-548 into the final phase of clinical testing. It has the potential to displace addictive opioids as an effective postsurgical painkiller, and there's obviously a big need here.

Another drug called VX-147 is also going into a pivotal clinical trial that could pave the way for approval. This drug treats APOL-1 mediated kidney disease, which causes large amounts of protein in the urine and eventually leads to kidney failure. It affects around 100,000 people in the U.S. and Europe 

At an earlier stage is VX-880, a cell therapy that could allow people with type 1 diabetes to produce their own insulin, creating a functional cure. We only have data from the first couple patients treated, but what we've seen so far is highly encouraging.

Now, thanks to the magic of Moore's Law, Xilinx's chips have finally reached the right balance of power and cost — just in time to play an important role in the growth of artificial intelligence, where their versatility is being put to full use. Xilinx's moment has finally arrived, and we're excited to recommend it today.

Xilinx invented the field programmable gate array (FPGA) in 1984. FPGAs were chips whose transistors could be instructed to execute specific commands using configurable logic blocks.

Software developers are borderline ecstatic about developing AI applications. But they also need the hardware to be able to keep up. This is where FPGAs shine, and where their flexibility and customization are becoming a whole lot more important.

Xilinx encourages this by providing software tools and forums to help its 2,250 global developers code using C++ or Python, then use FPGAs and a surrounding ecosystem to maximize the performance. Xilinx also occasionally brings its most talented developers in-house through acquisitions. 

Xilinx refers to itself as a "data-center-first" company whose greatest opportunity may be in the cloud. Large cloud vendors — including Amazon Web Services, Alibaba (NYSE: BABA), and Baidu (NASDAQ: BIDU) — are embracing FPGAs as a way to improve performance for customers and reduce their own power operating costs.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-8
tickerjournal.value:
There were 2.9 billion monthly active users on Facebook in the second quarter, and that's not even the whole picture. Factor in Facebook's audience on Instagram and WhatsApp, and the number of unique monthly active users across all of the social networking juggernaut's empire clocks in at a whopping 3.51 billion. We're talking about nearly half of the planet.

At first glance, it might seem as if Facebook has matured into a slow-moving cash cow, drifting out of the upper echelon of our growth-stock universe. It's a fair knock. Facebook's daily and monthly active users have only risen by 7% over the past year. Engagement is also just plodding along, as Facebook is serving up just 6% more ads than it was a year ago. However, that's just part of the story.

Marketers are paying more to reach targeted consumers, and ad revenue at Facebook has soared 56% over the past year given a 47% year-over-year surge in revenue per ad. Given the scalable nature of this business, net income more than doubled. Obviously, the second quarter of last year was unusual for most ad-supported platforms, but Facebook held up better than other marketing magnets. Ad revenue rose 10% at Facebook last year, roughly in step with the 12% increase in monthly active users.

Facebook isn't going away. It has too many hot platforms reaching even the jaded #CancelFacebook crowd. It also has more than $64 billion in the bank, so it has more than enough ammo to buy new outlets for growth. Facebook has come a long way, but in many ways, it's just getting started.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buys 2018-8
tickerjournal.value:
historic meltdown on July 26 (the largest market-cap loss in a single session, about $119 billion) didn't happen for no reason. The company's active-user count in the U.S. is stagnating, and it reported an actual decline in Europe. It continues to face controversy, and the areas where it is growing fastest could prove more difficult to monetize than its core user base. But we see a good opportunity here nonetheless. Its collection of platforms — Facebook itself, Instagram, WhatsApp — are incredibly sticky for users, with the vast majority of the world's Internet users on one or more of them. With statistics like that, user growth obviously can't go on forever. But the opportunity to further monetize existing, loyal users is massive.

After the bloodletting, Facebook is trading at around 28 times trailing earnings. Is that cheap? We think it is. Yes, operating margin is expected to fall from 44% last quarter into the mid-30% range as the company invests more on privacy, security, and transparency. But it's taking a page from Amazon's (NASDAQ: AMZN) playbook and spending money now to build a more powerful, durable platform. Facebook is choosing to take some short-term pain for some potentially very large long-term gains.

tickerjournal.value: very risky

Went public 2014-12.
***
Cancer immunotherapy has become a new hope in the war against cancer, and it holds remarkable promise.
has pioneered a novel approach: It removes a patient's T-cells from his or her body, engineers them to express fragments of a targeting antibody, and reintroduces them to the patient. This is called "chimeric antigen receptor T-cell therapy," or CAR-T. Juno also has a similar technology called T-cell receptor therapy (TCR) that targets proteins inside cancer cells, rather than on the cell surface.
***
Juno should be regarded as a typical early-stage biotech:  a relatively risky investment best spread out across a few different names

5 Potential Green Flags

The company has 10 different products against six different antigens in the clinic within the first half of 2016.
The company offers up compelling evidence that its "armored CAR" technology works in solid tumors, eliciting a strong T-cell-mediated immune response similar to what we've seen in blood cancers. Armored CAR uses the presence of secreted proteins within tumors to amplify the T cell response.
The company is able to quickly make progress in non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, where it earlier ran into some safety issues. While the company was able to produce very strong data in NHL at safe doses, it is looking to change the CAR-T it is using in this disease.
A pivotal trial for JCAR015 is launched, and the company keeps on schedule for a late-2016 or early 2017 filing for the CAR-T in acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL).
A further partnership brings more cash to Juno with compelling economic terms.

tickerjournal.value: We love companies that demystify business, erase inefficiencies, and bring secrets out into the light. Zillow (NASDAQ: ZG) has forever changed the way real estate works by putting the ability to browse housing prices right into the hands of consumers. It's another classic network effect: attractive to users because that's where the data is, attractive to real-estate pros because that's where the customers are, and decidedly unattractive to any would-be competitor hoping to win away all those monthly users. Better still, management continues to use its clout to move into new areas — rentals, new construction, and the sell side of the real estate transaction. This is a straightforward winner that should keep winning.

Virgin America has found success offering low-cost luxury flights to passengers eager to escape tight rows, uncomfortable seats, and lousy amenities.

100% American airline backed by a Knight of the British Empire and one of the world's great Rule Breakers: Sir Richard Branson.

Hawaii is the catalyst here; Virgin America begins service to Honolulu from San Francisco in November. Flights to Kahului kick off the following month, with plans to offer service from Los Angeles in 2016.

Buying into any airline is risky. Oil prices could skyrocket. Unionized employees could strike. Competition could catch up. And for all its advantages, Virgin America is still a relatively small airline, with a fleet of just 55 Airbus aircraft serving 24 destinations.

3 Potential Red Flags

Growth slows. Wayfair is priced for growth, so it is important that its growth rates remain high and consistent.
Management increases growth by pursuing low-quality customers. Management has been better at finding high-quality customers, but if there ever is a time where management acquires low-quality customers to continue short-term growth, that would be a red flag. These customers would be less likely to come back again, therefore having lower lifetime values.
Competition. Competition is already strong, but online, no one is standing in Wayfair's way. If a new upstart emerges or a company like Amazon.com (NASDAQ: AMZN) starts tackling this market, it would be very important to keep an eye on Wayfair for future developments.

Wayfair has become a world-leading destination for buying home products

Today, Wayfair operates through five brands: Birch Lane, Dwell Studio, AllModern, Joss & Main, and its namesake (by far the largest).

Almost 30% of millennials purchase essential goods online. That should help drive big growth in Wayfair's market as younger shoppers fill out their homes. The company says only 7% of home goods are purchased online today, and that number is expected to at least triple in the next decade, perhaps more. When compared to the 15% of apparel sales and 54% of electronic sales that come online, it's clear that furniture has a long way to run.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buy 2015-12
tickerjournal.value: Sports-camera maker GoPro (NASDAQ: GPRO) has had a terrible year, and Amabarella (NASDAQ: AMBA), a key supplier, has suffered right alongside. But Ambarella's image-processing systems-on-chips have a life of their own: About two-thirds of the company's sales come from other customers, and Ambarella is increasingly agnostic about where and how image capture takes place. It sells systems to DJI, the world's No. 1 drone maker, and we expect this market to take off as prices come down (Ambarella plans to capture part of it directly with its own drone). The company's new S2LM system for security and surveillance cameras captures full HD video with a six-month battery life. And it's got more tricks up its sleeve, having recently acquired computer-vision company VisLab — a bid for presence in smart cars and other high-end items. GoPro is still a big part of the game, too — we expect its six-camera, 360-degree virtual-reality arrays to capture a lot of interest. Video is a near-ubiquitous fact of life, and Ambarella remains ahead of the pack. While some on Wall Street think its strong performance can't continue, we think it's positioning itself well against the competition.

AMBA goes down with GoPro, but it does not sell to GoPro alone.

Ambarella is making the systems-on-chips for high-definition video and that's going to be a really big macro trend. You're going to see players like Intel and Qualcomm trying to get to be a part of this, but I'm not so certain that competition fear is as large as the market is pricing into it right now.

One of the things we look at is image quality and then compression efficiency, and Ambarella's got about a 30-40% lead on compression efficiency standards that [nobody] else in the market can even touch right now. Fermi Wang's been doing this for 25 years, and I just think that Ambarella has got a really strong position right now.

Ambarella's (NASDAQ: AMBA) stock got its lights knocked out by a short-seller report from controversial firm Citron Research back in June, and it's failed to find traction ever since. The business, however, has been a different story, and we think this disconnect offers investors a great opportunity. Ambarella's revenue for the past year is up 64% — a pace of growth that has actually been accelerating since 2012. Earnings per share are up 152% over the past year. Yet the stock now trades at only about 24 times trailing earnings. Sure, the S&P 500 has a P/E ratio of about 20.2, but you can bet its earnings aren't growing by triple digits. Ambarella's continued leadership in hi-def video systems-on-chips — and its entry in new product lines for drones, security, and autos — all point the way to continued growth.

tickerjournal.value: Shares of Ambarella (NASDAQ: AMBA) have come down sharply since July, so you can now grab this stock at a trailing P/E ratio of about 31. That doesn't sound like a bargain? GoPro remains a critical customer, but Ambarella has other tricks up its sleeve, like the new H1 chip for drones. The company's recently announced acquisition of Italy's VisLab, a specialist in computer vision and autonomous vehicles, points to some of the future directions we can expect.

To tweet or not to tweet is no longer a question. It's hard to find a celebrity, tastemaker, or influencer who doesn't have a Twitter (NYSE: TWTR) account these days.

Twitter's average monetizable daily active users stand at 206 million as of its latest quarter, an 11% increase over the past year. Like with Facebook, we're seeing Twitter get better at cashing in on its platform, with ad revenue growing a lot faster than its usage. Revenue soared 74% to $1.2 billion in the second quarter, which it reported last month. Twitter's top line grew even faster in the U.S., with a 79% year-over-year surge on its home turf that accounts for a little more than half of its total revenue.

Twitter is a survivor. It has overcome the controversy of banning some popular users who have violated the platform's terms of service, and it has outlasted its own limitations on the length of posts and complaints about the lack of post-editing features.

There are still more levers for Twitter to pull. In June, it announced that it would be rolling out its first premium-subscription service, Blue. We're also seeing advertisers flock to social media platforms, where they can reach folks who aren't frequenting traditional marketing outlets.

This is a good time to be Twitter. We feel that this is probably even a better time to be a Twitter shareholder.

Twitter (NYSE: TWTR) has had a tough go of it as a public company, mostly because it hasn't been able to grow its user base beyond its large and loyal core as quickly as hoped for. Its troubles became more visible when Dick Costolo stepped down as CEO, leaving the company rudderless. While co-founder Jack Dorsey stepped in as interim leader right away, we're excited to see him in the position full-time. Dorsey will continue splitting time between Twitter and the other company he runs, mobile payment pioneer Square, but we hope he can bring some new focus to Twitter's notoriously contentious boardroom and make some important changes to improve the platform. Already there have been some tough decisions — like a reported layoff of 8% of the company's workforce. Ultimately, it will take more than 140 characters to tell the company's story, but we don't think the stock will stay near its recent all-time low.

Planet Fitness (NYSE: PLNT) wasn't immune to the impacts of COVID-19, with total revenue falling 41% in 2020. But despite challenges, this plucky gym operator shows signs of better days ahead — including eking out $9.7 million in net income for the fourth quarter, even though revenue declined 30.1%.

While roughly 17% of U.S. fitness clubs closed permanently last year, no Planet Fitness gyms closed permanently and no franchisees went bankrupt. Furthermore, Planet Fitness and franchisees opened 130 gyms last year, including 41 gyms that opened in the fourth quarter. The company estimates that 90% of facilities are open today, which puts it in a good position to attract members and allows it to charge members for brick-and-mortar memberships.

The company found a new way to reach members through the Planet Fitness mobile app, one of the top three health and fitness apps for Apple (NASDAQ: AAPL) OS and Android. In a time when many gyms are struggling, the mobile app deepens Planet Fitness' engagement with its customers, as over 40% of members use the app to check gym capacity before leaving the house and exercise with a catalog of over 500 workouts.

Planet Fitness also rolled out a digital-only, paid subscription through its mobile app, which helped revenue during the pandemic. The paid subscription is a great new way to engage with prospective members, as 20% of digital subscribers aren't current Planet Fitness members. The paid subscription service also serves as a gateway to membership: Over 20% of nonmember subscribers enjoyed the experience so much that they become full brick-and-mortar members.

recently declared a 10-for-1 stock split as part of a plan to fortify its corporate governance.

The future is bright for Shopify. The stock has retreated the way many growth stocks have in recent months. It began this week trading for slightly less than half of where it was when it peaked in November. tickerjournal.name: Best buy: 2022-1
tickerjournal.value:
The popular e-commerce platform has proven mortal over the past two months, entering this holiday-abridged trading week more than a third below its recent high-water mark.

There's a lot to like when it comes to Shopify. It remains a hotbed for businesses of all sizes, and shoppers are having no problem finding them on Shopify's platform. Gross merchandise volume on the platform in its latest quarter (the third quarter, which ended in September) soared 35% to hit $41.8 billion. Gross payments volume rose even faster, soaring 49% to $20.5 billion, now accounting for nearly half of Shopify's e-commerce volume. Naturally, the even more potent holiday quarter that ended in December will deliver another record performance when Shopify makes those numbers official in mid-February.

Shopify works, and the story isn't exactly new to most of you. It's one of the most widely recommended stocks across our newsletter services, and it's a company that has an exciting founder-CEO at the helm. It's a global leader, and the future should be even brighter. On Tuesday, Shopify announced that it's partnering with China's JD.com (NASDAQ: JD) in a deal that will allow Shopify merchants in the U.S. to reach 550 million active customers in China on JD's cross-border JD Worldwide platform.

Shopify has been an all-weather winner, and we believe that the e-commerce market will continue to expand in the years to come. It's a smart way to play both consumer demand for online shopping and the merchants that need to embrace a digital storefront if they want to capitalize on the revolution. Shopify is a Best Buy Now this month.

tickerjournal.name: RB Recommendation 2022-4
tickerjournal.value:
If you're a merchant, you need to set up your shop where the shoppers are. If you're a shopper, you want to shop where you'll have the widest choice. As a marketplace grows in size, it becomes more attractive to the next merchant or shopper wondering where to sell or buy. This network effect can create a strong competitive moat. It certainly has for this month's re-recommendation: Etsy (NASDAQ: ETSY).

Etsy is a profitable company, earning nearly half a billion dollars in profit on $2.3 billion in revenue in 2021. Also last year, the company acquired Elo7, a marketplace for handmade items in Brazil, and Depop, on which buyers and sellers can offer or find quirky used clothing and accessories. We anticipate that Etsy will be able to use the search engine and customer analytics expertise it developed at Etsy.com, which has driven a 46% annual increase in GMS over the past three years, to improve and grow these acquired businesses.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2022-1
tickerjournal.value:
the platform posted impressive results in 2020, with gross merchandise sales increasing 107% over 2019. But as we write this article, shares are down almost 45% since November highs of nearly $297

Despite tough year-over-year comparisons, Etsy posted strong results in the third quarter. The platform continued to expand, with consolidated gross merchandise sales (which includes its Reverb, Depop, and Elo7 segments) increasing 17.9% over last year and active buyers increasing 37.8% year over year. Etsy's marketplace alone saw a 12.4% increase in gross merchandise sales, and the company showed that it is more than just a pandemic-dependent success, as non–face mask gross merchandise sales increased 23.7% over last year.

Etsy has also grown in stickiness and relevance. Etsy marketplace's habitual buyers (its most engaged users) grew an impressive 65% over last year, and the group continues to be the company's fastest-growing buyer segment. Etsy's active buyers increased their purchase frequency and the average value of their orders, driving a 20% growth in gross merchandise sales per active buyer, showing that the platform's stickiness is growing for more than just the most engaged users. Etsy's relevance has also increased; the company's app was the fifth-most-downloaded on the Apple app store during the third quarter.

But the company is hardly resting on its laurels. Over the last year, Etsy expanded its growth opportunities with key acquisitions like Depop (which expands Etsy's footprint in resale fashion) and Elo7 (known as the "Etsy of Brazil"). And while Etsy already had some presence in the country, Elo7 is one of Brazil's top 10 e-commerce sites and already has 1.9 million active buyers on its platform, so it is expected to increase Etsy's reach in that market.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-10
tickerjournal.value:
A few things about Etsy (NASDAQ: ETSY) make it a unique and attractive investment.

1. In this age of Amazon (NASDAQ: AMZN), Etsy is benefiting from the desire among a growing number of people to support local businesses.
2. It does not have to predict demand like other retailers do. Because sellers on Etsy act independently, they adapt dynamically to emerging demand. An example of this is the incident when a fly landed on Mike Pence's head during a vice presidential debate. Within hours, items related to this event were selling on Etsy. Contrast this to the operations of a typical retailer, which must predict demand with enough lead time to have the item made and shipped. If it predicts incorrectly, it faces inventory obsolescence risk. Etsy does not face this risk. This also allows it to operate a capital-light business. On the other hand, this also results in low barriers to entry. But this is partially offset by the network effect it benefits from. More buyers and sellers using the platform increase the attractiveness of Etsy for the next buyer or seller.
3. By selling unique, creative, higher-value items, it occupies a difficult-to-disrupt position in online retail. Items that sell on Etsy sell in very few other places, so Etsy faces far less price risk than a typical retailer does.
4.Etsy's is one of those businesses in which the total addressable market is very hard to estimate. This was CEO Josh Silverman's comment on Etsy's TAM in September 2021: "What I would suggest is that Etsy's addressable market is not a constraint to Etsy's growth in the next decade or two that we can imagine."
5. Etsy has begun to branch out into related businesses, bringing the knowledge it has acquired about its own workings to these acquired businesses. Prior to July 2021, Etsy had only made one acquisition (of Reverb, a marketplace for vintage musical instruments) in 2019. In July 2021, it acquired Elo7 (which operates Etsy's business model in Brazil) and Depop (a marketplace for used clothes).

With its market capitalization at only $29 billion, we anticipate there is still plenty of growth ahead of Etsy.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-6
tickerjournal.value:
If you're searching for a special gift — whether unique, personalized, or vintage — your hunt will inevitably lead to Etsy (NASDAQ: ETSY). Through Etsy.com and Reverb (which sells new and used music gear), Etsy operates online marketplaces that connect buyers with creative sellers.

Etsy specializes in the special, and that's a big part of the brand. As 88% of its users will tell you, Etsy is the place to find unique items (for yourself and others). The platform's uniqueness is powered by a network of sellers, which grew 67% to total 4.7 million sellers in the first quarter of 2021. Etsy's brand and seller network drew 90.6 million active buyers to the platform in the first quarter, up nearly 90% from last year.

To run a successful marketplace, you need engaged buyers. Etsy's habitual buyers (those with at least six purchases over the last year) grew 205% to 7.9 million in the first quarter of 2021. This increase, which was faster than total active buyer growth, points to Etsy becoming an increasingly sticky habit for users.

The growth in buyers and sellers drove impressive results for Etsy. Gross merchandise sales totaled $10.3 billion in 2020, an increase of 107% over 2019 — which was more than 2.5x faster than the growth of e-commerce industry sales. Etsy's growth continued into 2021, as gross merchandise sales increased 132% year over year to reach $3.1 billion for the first quarter.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buys 2018-12
tickerjournal.value: You can invest in the same trend with Etsy (NASDAQ: ETSY), a one-stop shop for small business. It's the best of both worlds: a major online channel with all the ease and convenience you'd expect that links shoppers to small businesses everywhere. Buyers know they'll find things on Etsy they won't see anywhere else. Sellers know there's no better way to reach a global audience, and they're willing to pay higher fees for the access. That's fueling huge revenue growth — up 30% in the past 12 months — and an even faster rise in cash flow, which has almost tripled from a year ago.

tickerjournal.name: Video Best Buys 2016-12
tickerjournal.value:
Well, Etsy should be a familiar name, at least to some of our members. I know I've personally done some of my holiday shopping on Etsy. But for those who aren't familiar, Etsy is an online platform to buy and sell homemade, vintage, and ultra-customizable items. These are things you're not going to typically go to an Amazon or an eBay to buy online.

The platform is big and growing. It has 1.7 million active sellers, 27 million active buyers, and 40 million items listed on the platform, and all those numbers are ticking up at a pretty good pace.

What's also interesting, here, is that 90% of the traffic to Etsy's site or app is all organic, so only a small fraction of the traffic to Etsy comes through things like advertising. That just shows the brand is relevant and resonating with a lot of people, and Etsy isn't having to spend a lot on marketing to attract buyers and sellers to the platform.

What's also interesting, here, is that seller base that Etsy is appealing to. Ninety-five percent of Etsy sellers run their shops from home. Over 80% are women and [half of those sellers sell only] on Etsy. That's the only place that they sell. And if sellers do sell in more than one place than Etsy, they're usually not selling on eBay or Amazon. They're usually selling at craft fairs and in person. So Etsy is really kind of the craft fair moving online in the 21st century. That's how I look at it and there's really no other Pepsi to their Coke. It's an interesting business today.

Management is guiding for 20-25% sales growth annualized over the next three years. They've actually raised guidance a couple of times for 2016 overall, so we should continue to see some healthy sales growth.

The company a few years ago moved beyond just that marketplace model where it generates a cut from each transaction on the platform. They started launching Seller Services in 2011. These are things like payments, shipping solutions, promoted listings and, most recently, web stores.
Etsy has a very unique relationship with its sellers who, like I mentioned earlier, aren't really selling anywhere else, so Etsy has a very personal relationship with those sellers. It can hear the pain points that those sellers have, and then now the company is able to provide solutions to those sellers. So Seller Services, like I said, only launched five years ago, but it now makes up over 55% of total sales, and that's really driving the bulk of the sales growth for the company today.

And there's still room for more Seller Services down the road. Etsy could help its sellers with things like external marketing on Google or Facebook, or inventory and product management, or whatever it might be. Etsy has such a unique relationship with its sellers who aren't selling anywhere else besides Etsy, so that leaves a lot of optionality for the company to build that relationship over time. So that will be an interesting thing to watch.

Also international growth is still in its infancy for the company. About 30% of gross merchandise sold is either from a buyer or a seller outside the U.S. Management thinks that number can get to 50% or higher in the coming years. The company has a strong balance sheet. Net cash of about $260 million, so they have a lot of cash that serves as a cushion and gives them room to invest in these different opportunities. Those are some of the things to be watching for in the coming years with Etsy.

pioneer of RAIN RFID.

Impinj's technology focuses on ultra-high-frequency RFID, allowing users to wirelessly identify, locate, and authenticate tens of thousands of units per hour, at relatively long range and minimal cost. It can even provide active information, with the tag itself transmitting data up to 100 meters away, so that the contents of a passing rail car can be easily tracked.

I'm especially impressed with a company that took a commanding lead in a commodity business, then set about strengthening that lead with a unique software platform.

Since being founded in 2000, Impinj has taken leading market share in tags and readers, with an estimated 65% share of the integrated circuits used in tags (what the company refers to as "endpoints") and 61% of the ICs used in readers or gateways.

So a year ago, Impinj launched ItemSense, its "operating system" that puts data in the cloud and provides APIs that developers can use however they want. Impinj claims to be the only company offering all three legs of the stool — gateways, connectivity, and software.

It's not hard to see the potential here. Imagine a fitting-room mirror that reads all the clothing brought inside, checks it against the retailer's inventory, and recommends complementary items and accessories to shoppers — while protecting against loss or theft. The tag might be woven into a label, so that the clothing is protected against counterfeiting or return fraud. And at home, your washing machine reads the label and adjusts its settings accordingly. Or imagine a smart trashcan inside an operating room that reads the labels from discarded medical supplies, recording both a billing event and an inventory note for reordering.

Impinj has helped create these applications for clients and more. It also powers Coca-Cola's (NYSE: KO) Freestyle soda machines, helps Delta Air Lines (NYSE: DAL) track each of the 120 million pieces of luggage it transports each year, and — according to reports from just days ago — is working with Amazon.com (NASDAQ: AMZN) on its Amazon Go initiative. (If you haven't seen this, it is Amazon's experiment with line-free, cashier-free retail stores).

We believe Impinj can grow sales by at least 20% annually over the next five years, and expand the bottom line even faster. That suggests revenue of over $250 million in five years' time. Even if the company's price-to-sales multiple slips from its current level of about 7 to around 5.5, that would mean roughly a doubling of the stock price. While the company is not yet profitable, it should report an adjusted profit this year and grow quickly from there. Moreover, its long history of operating losses means that when profits do come, they'll be largely tax-free for a long while.

the top dog in programmatic advertising has seen its stock fall sharply from last year's all-time highs. The Trade Desk has shed nearly half of its value since peaking at $114.09 in November.

The Trade Desk is a demand-side platform, or DSP, that allows brands and agencies to buy spots for their marketing missives within the realm of available advertising inventory. The Trade Desk stands out as a programmatic digital platform, crunching algorithms to help make a marketing campaign more effective across all ad formats.

Revenue rose 43% last year, up from a depressed 26% in 2020. Adjusted earnings per share rose 32% for all of 2021. Zoom in a little closer, and you see slowing growth as last year played out. Revenue and adjusted earnings per share climbed 24% and 14%, respectively. The comparisons were naturally going to get more challenging for the final frame of 2021. The world was starting to claw its way -- or, more importantly, spend its way -- out of the initial pandemic funk. We also had a lively political election season in 2020 accompanied by a seasonal spike in campaign spending.

The Trade Desk is still relevant. Its self-service, cloud-based platform is sticky to ad buyers. Customer retention continues to clock in above 95%, as it has for the last eight years. There are some near-term concerns, especially if the muddy cocktail of rising inflation and climbing interest rates triggers a recession. Brands and agencies are reluctant to spend a lot of money when consumers aren't willing to do the same.

It's a near-term concern worth watching, but the long-term outlook for The Trade Desk is undeniably bullish.

Teladoc's slide makes for an unflattering stock chart, but we think that there is still a lot to like when it comes to the market leader in telehealth. We feel that the future is promising for virtual medical consultations, and investors who have been unloading Teladoc simply because we're clawing our way out of the pandemic and able to see doctors, psychologists, and nutritionists in person underestimate what Teladoc brings to the table. 

Teladoc is still growing. Revenue soared 81% in its latest quarter. The results are inflated by the Livongo Health acquisition, which didn't close until a third of the way through the fourth quarter of 2020, but organic growth is still checking in with a picture of health. The 3.9 million virtual visits that Teladoc completed in the third quarter of this year were 37% ahead of where they stood a year earlier, when many guidance seekers didn't have much of a choice but to turn to virtual solutions.   

The pandemic accelerated market awareness of telemedicine, and the ability to receive medical attention for a growing number of ailments within minutes and without having to leave the home isn't going away. You don't get a taste of the future, only to clamor for the days of long stays leafing through old magazines in crowded waiting rooms. Teladoc stock has been hit hard, and it's fair to say that this is a more competitive marketplace than it was when we initially gave the stock the nod in 2017. We feel that time will deliver the cure to the market's current pessimism, making Teladoc a Best Buy Now this month.

Teladoc ended 2020 with 51.8 million paid U.S. members, and management expects to end this year with 51 million to 52 million members. That's no growth at all.

Because access fees aren't driven only by the number of members or even by the price but by the number of services contracted by a client. And this has been growing rapidly. Put another way, Teladoc's $737.4 million in U.S. access fees during 2020 amounted to just $14.24 per paid member, or $1.19 per month. There is room to move this higher not simply by hiking fees but by adding more access that can later translate to more service fees.

While the company is perhaps most associated with general wellness services — single-visit concerns like colds and flus — it has already added services around dermatology and mental health. These latter categories tend to drive more repeat visits and thus higher service utilization.

And this year, the company is launching Primary360, its virtual primary care service. What began as a pilot program in 2019 has grown to more than 70 distinct diagnoses, aimed at spotting chronic conditions early. And Gorevic says there are more than 100 diagnostic opportunities in the pipeline for Primary360. 

Teladoc is a videoconferencing platform, certainly, but that's increasingly the commodity part of its business. The real meat — and the competitive moat — is in the increasing amount of data the company has and how it can use the platform to improve outcomes.

MongoDB helps companies rethink databases without the heavy reliance on centralized, regularly upgraded hardware. That may not sound sexy, but it's a huge business. But the economic reopening impacted Pinterest's user growth, and in the second quarter, global MAUs increased only 9% year over year and fell 5% when compared with the first quarter of 2021. This sequential decline helped drag Pinterest's share prices down roughly 24% from July 29 to Sept. 14. But while a decline in users can be concerning, Pinterest's business is stronger than its falling share price might suggest — which we believe translates into a timely buying opportunity.

Part of what makes Pinterest unique is the fact that ads don't detract from user experiences like they do on other social media platforms. Instead, ads are part of the experience and help users go from searching for inspiration to taking action — and to shopping. This model helps attract advertisers to the platform and boosts revenue. Pinterest's total global average revenue per user (ARPU) grew 89% in the second quarter to total $1.32, and U.S. ARPU grew 103% year over year to total $5.08.

While the domestic growth was impressive, it was outshone by international ARPU, which grew 163% year over year and totaled $0.36 in the second quarter. But Pinterest is still in the early innings for international ARPU, and catching up to U.S. levels represents a significant growth opportunity. Pinterest aims to capture it by continuing to grow its international advertiser base, increase shoppable content, and supply users with more and more relevant ads.

Strong advertiser performance buoyed Pinterest's top-line growth as well. Growth in international advertisers, strong demand from large retail advertisers, and continued growth from small advertisers drove an impressive 125% year-over-year increase in revenues during the second quarter. And despite the economic reopening, Pinterest reported net income of $69 million in the second quarter of 2021, a big improvement over net losses of $101 million in the second quarter of 2020.

Despite the fall in share price, sequential declines in monthly active users, and tough year-over-year comparisons in the upcoming quarter, we believe Pinterest's business is stronger than some might think. That's due not only to its platform's uniqueness but to its incredible ARPU story, ability to attract advertisers, and potential to grow revenues.

The company was the first to bring price transparency in prescription drugs to U.S. consumers and has grown its business into an ecosystem that includes subscriptions, pharmaceutical manufacturer solutions, and a telehealth marketplace. That expanding ecosystem is what has earned GoodRx a place on our Best Buys Now list this month.

While GoodRx's flagship service provides price transparency and discounts, its subscriptions (GoodRx Gold and Kroger Savings Club) provide even greater discounts to consumers and supply the company with recurring revenue. The number of subscriptions increased 86% year over year to total more than 1 million in the second quarter, which drove a 125% year-over-year growth in subscription revenue.

GoodRx is finding new ways to expand subscriptions, including partnering with DoorDash and USAA to provide DoorDash employees and USAA's 13 million members with discounted access to the GoodRx Gold subscription.

GoodRx also sees a big opportunity in helping pharmaceutical manufacturers connect with customers. Pharmaceutical manufacturer solutions are GoodRx's fastest-growing segment, and revenue nearly tripled since last year. GoodRx has a good track record with its current partners, reporting net revenue retention of more than 150% year over year, and aims to continue to expand these relationships. GoodRx already has relationships with 19 of the top 20 pharmaceutical manufacturers but has room to grow, as it has only penetrated about 4% of the top 20 manufacturers' brands. There's also plenty of room for new partnerships, as GoodRx has relationships with about 10% of the estimated 550 U.S. pharmaceutical manufacturers.

GoodRx is utilizing partnerships to expand the relevance and helpfulness of its network, too. It recently partnered with Surescripts, which is the leading U.S. health information network (that connects electronic health records, pharmacies, and health systems) and delivered almost 2 billion electronic prescriptions in 2020. Under the partnership, GoodRx's real-time pricing data will be included in electronic health records and supplied through Surescripts' Real-Time Prescription Benefit in prescriptions for uninsured patients or for those whose price information isn't available.

With increasing subscriptions, valuable pharmaceutical manufacturer relationships, and an important partnership within health information, GoodRx is not only growing revenues (which were up 43% year over year in the second quarter); it is also expanding its ecosystem, growing in importance within the healthcare space, and laying a foundation for future growth.

Last year, according to Newzoo, global video game industry revenues grew 23.1% year over year, to total nearly $178 billion — that's larger than the global film, television, and streaming market (which posted revenues of $101 billion in 2019). The boost in video game revenues was partly helped by COVID-19 restrictions, and while 2021 the video game industry expected to decline slightly (due to economic reopenings), it is on track to grow to nearly $205 billion in 2023. And with a market that large, there are a lot of games to play. But here's a bit of information to consider: An estimated 53% of the top 1,000 mobile games and roughly 50% of all video games (across 20 different platforms) were created with the help of one company: Unity Software (NYSE: U).

Unity is a compelling picks-and-shovels play, as its platform is used to create, run, and monetize 2D and 3D content for video games and other industries (such as architecture and automotive). Unity has made a habit of strong top-line growth, with second-quarter revenue up 48% over the prior-year period — marking the 11th consecutive quarter of at least 30% growth. It's been successful at building up its customer base as well, with a 24% growth in large customers (those spending more than $100,000) and adding three new automotive manufacturers during the quarter. Additionally, Unity reports a dollar-based net retention of 142%, which means that customers stay and increase their spending with Unity.

Despite impressive growth, this story is far from over. Unity has a long runway for growth; its 2020 revenue made up less than 3%  of its $29 billion addressable market ($12 billion in gaming and $17 billion in other industries). The company also aims to increase its growth in the video game markets by winning over artists, a group Unity believes will grow in size and in importance, as art is expected to become a major factor in creating compelling game content. One step in winning over artists was the acquisition of Interactive Data Visualization, the creator of SpeedTree. Unity believes that deeper integration of SpeedTree into its ecosystem will enhance artist workflows and environment creation capabilities.

With strong momentum, impressive customer retention, a long runway for growth, and a plan to expand its share of the video game market, we believe Unity is a compelling investment and an impressive picks-and-shovels play.

tickerjournal.value:
An independent monitoring committee took a peep at the blinded data from an ongoing study of the company's device being used in non-small cell lung cancer and realized that it was very likely going to be successful. 

Novocure has a unique technology for fighting cancer called tumor-treating fields. The idea is that surrounding a tumor within a charged field prevents cancer cells from successfully dividing. As they attempt the process, two highly charged spindles that draw the new cells apart are formed and then are locked up by the field. The cells ultimately die; instead of one cell becoming two, it becomes zero.

the company was selling a device in 2019 called Optune for the treatment of glioblastoma multiforme (GBM), the most common form of brain cancer. The device produces a tuned electric field that stops tumor cells within it from dividing, but it only works when it's worn and is turned on. Therefore, patients need to shave their heads and wear the device as close to 24/7 as possible.

At this point, the Optune is recommended as a first-line treatment for GBM after surgery (when possible) and radiation (when appropriate). Around 40% of patients with GBM do indeed end up using the Optune device.

As noted above, the company's ongoing phase 3 NSCLC trial (called LUNAR) is going to complete sooner than expected and is highly likely to yield positive results. Another phase 3 trial in ovarian cancer (INNOVATE-3) will yield results even sooner. An interim analysis is imminent, and we should have final results of both trials next year. That means the company is months away from potentially increasing its addressable market roughly 16-fold.

We should also hear an interim analysis from the company's PANOVA trial in pancreatic cancer next year, as well as final data from the METIS study looking at tumor-treating fields in treating brain metastases from lung cancer. The company recently won a breakthrough designation from the FDA for the use of its device in treating liver cancer, and more data from that study is expected next year too. All told, the company is conducting four pivotal trials and two phase 2 trials and is doing preclinical evaluation in nearly a dozen other cancers.

Then there's geographic expansion. Novocure has, until recently, focused most of its efforts in the U.S., which accounted for almost 70% of revenue in 2020. (A further 19% came from Germany, with the rest of Europe contributing little.) That is changing. The company has recently gotten reimbursement agreements in more European countries and continues to expand there. In September 2018, the company entered into a partnership with Zai Lab (NASDAQ: ZLAB) to sell its devices in China, and it is starting to see that market gain momentum.

Despite a lot of upcoming news flow, the market has been focused on something even closer at hand: plateauing sales in GBM.

Novocure has already transformed the treatment of brain cancer, and it stands poised to grow its market opportunity more than an order of magnitude. And it looks to the future without any visible competition, protected by patents, know-how, data, and a long head start. The field of oncology has long focused on three ways to fight cancer: surgery, radiation, and drugs. This truly is a fourth modality that can fit in right alongside the others and add to our ability to halt the most deadly of diseases.

The share price of NovoCure (NASDAQ: NVCR) has been nearly cut in half since its June peak. We love to add to our winners here at Rule Breakers, and we don't necessarily chase after declining stocks. But this is just too good an opportunity to pass up.

The last major news from NovoCure came back in April, when the company announced interim results from its ongoing study of its tumor-treating field (TTF) device in non-small cell lung cancer. They were so strong that the independent monitoring committee told the company it could complete the study without enrolling further patients into the control arm — indeed, that it might be unethical to do so. The stock shot up around 40% on that announcement. Since then, we've had even more positive news in liver cancer (although the market didn't seem to view it that way).

As we stand, NovoCure shares are now cheaper than they were before the April announcement. That doesn't make a whole lot of sense, especially considering that the lung cancer market is many times the size of the company's current core market in glioblastoma. And while growth in glioblastoma might be slowing (we'll find out more when NovoCure reports earnings on Oct. 28), that's not going to matter to a company eyeing approvals in multiple new indications over the next few years.

Whether it's when Cloudflare itself gets hacked or when it has had to show a controversial customer the door, Prince doesn't shy away from the facing the music.

The stock isn't cheap. Cloudflare trades at a hearty 70 times trailing revenue. There's no profit multiple since it's still in the red. We're not afraid of stocks that seem expensive around here. Good things happen to companies growing quickly and taking market share despite a lofty valuation. However, if market sentiment starts to sour, we could see quality growth stocks trading at high multiples fall sharply in the rotation.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy 2021-6

It is a content delivery network (CDN), somewhat like fellow Rule Breaker Fastly (NYSE: FSLY). But while Fastly is focused on leveraging superior hardware and software into lightning-fast content updates, Cloudflare has a particular focus on security. 

Cloudflare is perhaps best known for protecting public-facing websites. The company prevents DDoS attacks — in which hackers flood a website with massive quantities of fake traffic to the point that it can't serve anyone — in part by using its own distributed servers as a proxy for clients' sites.

These days, you might hear other buzzwords: Zero Trust Network Access and Secure Access Service Edge (SASE, pronounced "sassy," if you want to sound in-the-know). Cloudflare is at the center of both.

tickerjournal.name: Best Buy 2021-10
