This year has been challenging for Peloton, and we're not just talking about fitness centers getting back to business. Peloton issued a voluntary recall of its treadmills in May after more than 70 injury reports involving children and pets — including a child's fatality. Federal subpoenas would follow.

This summer delivered more bad news. The stock took a hit after a rare quarterly miss, accompanied by problematic near-term guidance. Investors were also surprised by a larger-than-expected price cut on Peloton's signature bike.

We're still lacing up our workout shoes, hopping on, and ready to put our mettle to the stationary bike pedal. We're making Peloton a Best Buy Now for the first time since July of last year. We feel that Peloton's popularity is far from peaking, and not just because retention is going to be high when folks make that beefy initial investment for a treadmill or stationary bike.

Peloton closed out fiscal 2021 with 2.33 million connected-fitness subscribers, more than doubling over the course of the year. It expects to have 3.63 million connected-fitness subscribers by next summer. The number of folks paying for digital subscriptions without owning Peloton hardware is expected to grow even faster.

Peloton the company is holding up better than Peloton the investment. Churn remains reasonably low, and its 12-month retention rate is an encouraging 92%. The recent $400 price cut on its original bike — down to $1,495, or $39 a month with 39-month financing — is also not a red flag. Lower price points are necessary for the product to go mainstream.

The stock has shed nearly half of its value since peaking in January, but this is not half the company that it used to be. We feel it can beat the market after a year of setbacks. Ready to spin? Peloton is a Best Buys Now recommendation.

the company has been shadowed by news of a different sort: the recall of all its treadmills

These are people who pay $12.99 for access to Peloton content but don't necessarily have the company's hardware.

operates two of the world's four highest-grossing dating apps. It's not the top dog in this niche, but it is gaining ground on Tinder parent Match Group (NASDAQ: MTCH).

Tinder and Bumble are the planet's two most successful online dating apps, and one thing they have in common is that Whitney Wolfe Herd is a founder of both platforms. Herd was a Tinder co-founder when the game-changing hook-up app launched in 2012, leaving in the springtime of 2014 to launch Bumble a few months later. You're not in the right place at the right time — twice — by accident.

Giving women more control and power isn't just a dynamic on the app itself; it starts at the top of the org chart. Three of the four members of Bumble's executive team are female. Women also make up 8 of its 11 board members.

Revenue soared 36% in 2019, well ahead of the much-larger Match Group with its 19% top-line advance that year. Bumble and Match Group saw their revenue climb 19% and 17%, respectively, in 2020.

However, given the roughly comparable revenue multiples of the two stocks, Bumble is still the pick we're going with this month. Bumble is earlier in its growth cycle, with a much longer runway for its disruptive model.

tickerjournal.name: Best buy: 2022-1

Roblox (NYSE: RBLX) impressed us with its third-quarter report, but since then, investors have been slowly backing away from the virtual-world-building platform.

While we don't get to see fourth-quarter earnings until February, we do have some idea of what is coming. The company released metrics for the month of November, so we got a glimpse of how things were shaping up following the third quarter. The numbers show strong increases in revenue, daily active users (DAUs), hours engaged, and bookings — but a slight decrease in bookings per user. It's a familiar story: The company is doing great, but maybe not quite as great as Wall Street had hoped for at its peak expectations. And the stock is down 44% from the high it set in late November.

At this point, Roblox is trading at about 16.7 times estimated 2021 revenue. That's certainly not cheap, but Roblox has positioned itself as a unique, global platform where individuals can explore, companies can leverage new ideas, and brands can find a new virtual foothold. It attracts developers with its system of payouts, and it attracts users by having established itself as the front door to the metaverse.

We think the current price anticipates a fairly sharp deceleration of growth. And it's true that revenue can't keep growing at a triple-digit pace like it did last year. But both DAUs and hours engaged continue to grow at an impressive pace (indeed, they accelerated somewhat from the second and third quarters of last year). We're less concerned about the monetization side of the business at this early stage, as long as more users keep engaging with the platform and cash continues to roll in.

tickerjournal.value:
a digital metaverse — in which users build and share virtual worlds. 

Today, there are more than 20 million experiences on Roblox, from simple blocky environments you walk around to meticulously textured and detailed worlds with carefully designed gameplay. On the average day during the month of July, 46.6 million unique users were active on the platform. The majority of users on the platform are now older than 13, and this remains the fastest-growing age demographic.

Roblox makes its money through virtual currency, called Robux, that players buy and use for customized avatars and other in-game items. The content is user generated. But the legions of young creators who make virtual worlds have been joined by sophisticated studios and professional game designers. There is a profit motive here — the developers keep a share of the Robux they collect in their games and exchange it back to the company. In 2020, over 300 developers earned $100,000 or more on the platform, and the company paid out a total of $328.7 million to content creators.

In 2020, it brought in $923.9 million in revenue, up 81.7% from the prior year. Bookings, which tracks the actual purchase of virtual currency and in-game items (with revenue mostly recognized over a 23-month period), climbed 35% to $665.5 million.

As much as it is a gaming space, it is also a social media platform — users connect with friends in environments of their choice, chat, explore, and maybe play a game. For users who grow up on the platform, it's not clear that they will "graduate" to other forms of social media. And indeed, we're now seeing that users stick with Roblox as they age — even as other, older newcomers join in.

In the second quarter, users spent 9.7 billion hours on Roblox — or about 2.5 hours per active user per day.

Upstart's growth in this core market is nowhere near over, but the company is proving that it can move in other directions as well. The company signaled a move into auto loans last year when it acquired Prodigy Software. This is the year that business becomes a reality -- indeed, the company expects to process $1.5 billion in auto loans during 2022. But that, too, is just a beginning. The company estimates that $1 trillion worth of cars are sold in the U.S. each year, and most of them are financed. It's a clear sign that Upstart's disruption of consumer lending is still in early innings.

Of course, we've gotten used to the idea that cloud software companies in their hypergrowth phase come at a steep price. For better or worse, that's not really the case anymore. Trading at a little more than 9 times sales no longer sounds like a nosebleed multiple for a company that has proved it can turn fast growth and high transaction volume into real cash flow.

Upstart shares have fallen sharply since briefly topping $400 in October, but the business is still booming. The stock shot higher earlier this week after the company reported blowout financial results. Upstart clocked in with revenue of $305 million for the fourth quarter, well ahead of the $255 million to $265 million it was targeting three months earlier. Revenue rose 252%, accelerating from the 250% year-over-year increase it posted in the third quarter. Throw in record profits and a share buyback, and you start thinking that maybe it's not just the company that should be buying Upstart stock while it continues to trade at a steep discount to its autumn peak.

The future is bright for Upstart, but the stock will remain volatile. Upstart will need to expand its banking partners, and it will need to broaden its offerings to cover more financial services products and to reach more than just nonconventional borrowers. It has the tech tools and advantage to make these things happen. The strategies will take time to play out, of course, and that's why -- for the third and final time -- there's no point in bragging about timing in the short run.

tickerjournal.name: RB Best Buy 2021-12
tickerjournal.value:
It's fair to say that Upstart (NASDAQ: UPST) has been on our minds quite a bit this fall, and by fall, I mean both the autumn season and the stock's sharp drop. We added the disruptive provider of next-gen creditworthiness ratings to our scorecard in late September, and it made the cut as a Best Buy Now in November. With its fundamentals still strong and the price point even more compelling, it remains a Best Buy Now this month.

That's three nods of affirmation in the fall season. Now let's talk about the fall reason. Upstart has shed more than half of its value since peaking in mid-October, and the carnage is only mildly kinder from our initial entry point a few weeks earlier. The primary catalyst for the stock's slide is the poorly received third-quarter results it served up in early November.

The financial update was a lot stronger than the market's negative reaction suggests. Revenue soared 250% to $228 million, well exceeding both the company's earlier guidance and analyst expectations. Its adjusted profit was nearly double what it was bracing investors for just three months earlier. Its outlook for the current quarter was also encouraging. What tripped up the stock?

The stock's heady run in the months leading up to its mid-October high likely heightened market expectations to unrealistic levels. There were also some analyst concerns about the lack of major banking partners hopping on the Upstart platform as well as the company's inability to quantify the auto financing opportunity that it's starting to crack.

We are big believers in Upstart's platform, which uses artificial intelligence to arrive at a more accurate risk profile in sizing up borrower applications. The stock's valuation will invite volatility until Upstart grows into its true potential. But if you can stomach the risks for a piece of a company that is disrupting the archaic lending credit scores market, which is ripe for upending, we feel that Upstart is a Best Buy Now at this point.

hit a downdraft after reporting third-quarter earnings. But you really can't fault the company or its performance. And it sees a very strong fourth quarter shaping up, too.

If you're wondering about the bigger picture at this AI-guided lending platform, co-founder and CEO Dave Girouard summed it up this way: "Since Upstart's IPO a year ago, we've more than tripled our revenue, tripled our profits, tripled the number of banks and credit unions on our platform, and tripled the number of auto dealerships we serve. With that many 3s, Upstart is becoming the Steph Curry of the FinTech industry."

Indeed, it's the bigger picture that explains the market's reaction, and how we think we should act as investors. Upstart stock rose 1,444% from its debut price of $26 in December 2020 to its October 2021 high of $401.49. Even after letting off a lot of steam, it's still up over 800% in less than a year. To say that's remarkable is a profound understatement. And while that kind of short-term enthusiasm can lead to the kind of volatility we've seen recently, it is also driven by amazing performance and a massive opportunity. If Upstart continues to execute the way it has been, this $19 billion company will eventually be much, much larger.

leaning on artificial intelligence (AI) to arrive at what it believes is a true risk profile. Upstart's proprietary machine learning models help fine-tune the identification of risk, approving more loan seekers than conventional models that are based on outdated credit scores.

fast-growing online retailer of pet food, supplies, and other related products that is gaining market share in an already expanding industry.

TaskUs helps other companies with customer support, content moderation, and data annotation for the training of AI. Its services and culture are designed to serve the needs of technology companies, which have grown rapidly in the last decade. Since tech companies are focused primarily on product development, operational needs can grow so quickly that the customer experience suffers. At this point, they often turn to TaskUs, which trains a team to take this work off their hands.

TaskUs focuses on partnering with clients early, as it did with Uber Technologies (NYSE: UBER) in 2013, and growing with them. Founded only 13 years ago, TaskUs generated $673 million in revenue in the 12 months ending Sept. 30, on which it earned operating income of $88 million (13% margin). Its revenue grew at a compound annualized rate of 60% between 2017 and 2020. We believe the current market capitalization of $4.17 billion is low when considered in light of its historical and prospective revenue growth and its profitability.

tickerjournal.value:
TaskUs provides business process outsourcing services to fast-growing, internet-based companies such as Meta Platforms (NASDAQ: FB), DoorDash (NYSE: DASH), Uber Technologies (NYSE: UBER), and Zoom Video Communications (NASDAQ: ZM). TaskUs' services to its clients fall into three categories:

customer support (handling customer queries about services or their account)
content moderation (flagging or deleting inappropriate content)
data annotation for the training of AI systems

It stands ready to step in and take operational tasks off the hands of the overburdened tech company employees, ensuring that operations run smoothly and customers have a pleasant experience.

One of the things we like about TaskUs is that it doesn't need to sell itself too hard. In the three years from 2018 to 2020, 52% of new clients came from referrals or when they contacted TaskUs themselves. The company's "win rate" for new clients in 2020 was 56%, and the total for 2018 to 2020 was 42%. This means that the company was awarded contracts worth $0.42 for every $1 of proposal value it submitted to new clients in that period.

There is no shortage of business process outsourcing providers. The giants in the industry include Accenture (NYSE: ACN), Tata Consultancy Services (NSEI: TCS), and Cognizant Technology Solutions (NASDAQ: CTSH). What differentiates TaskUs is its focus on maintaining a culture that matches that of its tech company clients. This means creating a positive work environment with great benefits that results in happy, engaged employees.

The company is dispersed geographically, with senior leadership located in the U.S. and the majority of employees located in the Philippines. This physical separation will make it harder for senior leadership to connect with employees and maintain the culture.

Uber is so much more than a way to drive you home safely. Beyond its namesake Uber and Uber Eats platforms, this is a tech giant that's nailing last-mile logistics. Uber is expanding the breadth of products that it can deliver to your doorstep, and don't overlook its fast-growing freight logistics business. It looks to be on the brink of something that would make even value investors sit up and take notice.

But during the pandemic, it became much more, and in the U.S. alone, the food-delivery market more than doubled during lockdowns. Uber's delivery business grew as well, increasing from roughly $1.4 billion in revenue in 2019 to $8.4 billion in 2021. It would be tempting to write this growth off as a strange benefit of the stay-at-home orders and social distancing of the pandemic. And while it's true that the pandemic beefed up revenues for food-delivery services, delivery as a service is not going away.

Uber One is special, even if most competitors also have premium-tier subscription offerings. Smaller ride-hailing rival Lyft (NASDAQ: LYFT) is in no hurry to dive into food delivery directly, and Uber Eats competitors DoorDash (NYSE: DASH) and Grubhub will probably never drive you to your favorite music festival. This leaves Uber One -- at a reasonable $9.99 a month -- as the only global premium service that covers both mobility and direct delivery.

Uber also has its freight business, which leverages Uber technology to connect carriers and shippers. At $2.1 billion in revenue, it is the smallest of Uber's business segments even though it has nearly tripled since 2019. But there is plenty of room to grow, as Uber can utilize Uber freight to potentially play in the last-mile logistics space, white labeling freight forwarding in a manner similar to DoorDash's but on a global scale.

the travel lodging industry looks very different coming out of the pandemic. Travelers want more, and they're getting it by renting entire homes or even spare rooms at a fraction of the cost of conventional lodging on a square-foot basis.

But Airbnb has finally turned that corner and is highly profitable on a trailing business. It has generated nearly $2 billion in free cash flow over the past 12 months after stripping out the impact of close to $900 million in stock-based compensation.

Airbnb is stronger than it was before the pandemic, and we're not just talking about its consistent profitability and the gobs of free cash flow it's generating. Trailing revenue for bellwether hoteliers including Marriott (NASDAQ: MAR) and Hilton (NYSE: HLT) is still well below what they rang up in 2019, but Airbnb is faring considerably better. Revenue and gross booking value for its latest quarter were 73% higher than in the same period in 2019, a refreshing combination of a 24% increase in nights and experiences booked stacked on top of a 40% surge in average daily rates.

Regulations have been a pressure point for Airbnb and its hosts.
Valuation risks are real. Airbnb's trailing revenue and earnings multiples are high -- at 10 and 60, respectively.

tickerjournal.name: RB Recommendation
tickerjournal.value:
this elevator is going down first before we start heading in the right direction.

PubMatic operates a cloud-based supply side platform for programmatic advertising. Unlike The Trade Desk (NASDAQ: TTD) -- the demand-side specialist that's been a scintillating 16-bagger since our initial recommendation in early 2017 -- PubMatic works the other end of the advertising equation. It serves digital content publishers with ad space to sell. It plays nice with demand-side platforms, and Trade Desk is even a PubMatic partner, but its aim is ultimately to maximize the monetization potential of websites, mobile apps, and other online content providers.

This is a highly fragmented market, but PubMatic is unique in that it owns and operates its own ad-serving infrastructure. Most of its peers lean on public cloud-hosting giants to make their software hum, but PubMatic also owns all of the networking and hardware of its business. 

The business is growing. When PubMatic went public two years ago, its prospectus bragged about the platform serving 134 billion ad impressions a day. That's a big number, but PubMatic is delivering roughly 400 billion daily ads just two years later. Revenue has picked up since the 15% increase it posted for all of 2019. The top line rose 31% in 2020, accelerating to 53% last year, though it slowed to 27% year-over-year growth in its latest quarter. PubMatic's long-term growth target is 20% or more, and it has reached that goal in each of the past eight quarters.

The business is profitable. If its growth objective feels conservative for a company toiling away in the booming niches of connected TV, mobile, and online video, it's because over the past 16 years, PubMatic has been run like a company that didn't need to go public. It is fiscally prudent, and that shows even now as a public company in a world in which so many cloud stocks are grappling with profitability. PubMatic has come through with 13 consecutive quarters of positive net income. Shifting to adjusted EBITDA, that quarterly streak is up to 25 at last count.

tickerjournal.name: RB Recommendation: 2022-10
tickerjournal.value:
Celsius champions a growing line of functional fruit-flavored sparkling beverages. At the heart of the product pitch is its proprietary Meta Plus formula that leans on green tea with ECGC, ginger, and guarana to trigger thermogenesis, increasing your temperature by half a degree to boost your metabolic rate. The health and wellness claim is that Celsius can accelerate your metabolism, burning body fat faster when combined with a healthy diet and ideally consumed just before engaging in moderate exercise.

accelerating growth at a time when many companies are shifting in reverse.

As a bonus, Celsius has been marginally profitable in each of those years. It's an impressive feat for one of the fastest-growing players in the wide consumer packaged goods universe as it invests in expanding its shelf space and promotional displays. The triple-digit revenue growth isn't sustainable, sure, but there's a long runway here. 

PepsiCo (NASDAQ: PEP) and Celsius struck a financial partnership in August. The pop star invested $550 million for an 8.5% convertible preferred share stake in Celsius. The cash will boost Celsius' balance sheet when it reports its third-quarter results next month.

TransMedics has no competition in the heart market. In lungs and liver, there is one other provider (for each organ) of a similar machine. We believe that working with multiple organs is a competitive advantage for TransMedics. If you're a hospital, why would you buy your heart machine from TransMedics and your lung machine from Xvivo Perfusion (OM:XVIVO) if there is no significant difference between them in terms of performance and cost? It is simply easier to deal with one vendor: You order supplies from the same place, you get training from the same company, and perhaps you might get a discount for purchasing multiple machines. 

Some of TransMedics' key patents expired in 2021. Competitors can now use the freely available intellectual property to bring competing machines to market. Despite this, we still believe the company has a deep competitive moat because developing medical devices is a lengthy and expensive process. TransMedics has had to run multiple clinical trials to prove to regulators and hospitals that its OCS is safe and effective.

tickerjournal.name: RB Recommendation
tickerjournal.value:
The Monday.com Work OS is an open platform that organizations can use to build software applications and work management tools. You don't need to be a software engineer to get going. Monday.com Work OS consists of different workspace boards, and each one is basically a combination of a sophisticated spreadsheet and a no-code database. It plays nice with third-party apps, is powerful but simple, and is flexible enough to tackle a wide variety of tasks.

Revenue rose 65% in its latest quarter, up 68% on a foreign exchange-adjusted basis. We've seen the top-line jumps decelerate in each of the past four reports, but we're not going to shake our heads at 68% currency-neutral growth in this otherwise challenging climate.

many of the over 152,000 customers -- spanning more than 200 industries in over 200 countries -- are small accounts. The goal here is to nurture them to the point that they become enterprise users that spend at an accelerated rate.

Monday.com has yet to report a quarterly profit since going public 18 months ago, and it was posting losses for several years before its Wall Street debut. This is what a growth stock looks like early in its life cycle.

Specifically, the company has more than $850 million in cash and short-term investments on its balance sheet, nearly 10 times the total debt that it's currently carrying on its books. It's not going to run out of money anytime soon.

Everbridge (EVBG) provides software communications and enterprise safety applications.

After a strong beat and raise quarter reported in late February, analysts have significantly raised EPS estimates, looking for 124% growth this year and another +23% in 2024. Everbridge delivered quarterly earnings of $0.39 per share, beating the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $0.31 per share for an earnings surprise of 25.81%.

Over the last four quarters, the company has surpassed consensus EPS estimates four times. Revenues of $117.13 million eclipsed the Zacks Consensus Estimate by 0.85%. Everbridge management sees FY23 EPS of $1.48-$1.52, vs the February consensus of $1.36, and FY23 revenue of $456.0M-$462.0M, vs. consensus of $457.69M. This makes the stock a relative bargain in Software on a price-to-sales basis of just 2.8X vs. an industry range of 5-10X.

tickerjournal.name: 7 best for April 2023 from Zack.
tickerjournal.value:
Volvo (VLVLY) manufactures cars, trucks, buses, construction equipment, and diesel engines along with marine and industrial engines. Its offerings also include insurance, rental services, spare parts, and preventive maintenance among other services.

The company recently reported sales of 51,286 cars in February, up 22% year over year. The growth was attributed to its Recharge hybrid vehicles, which made up 40% of global car sales while its fully electric car sales increased an impressive 187% YoY and accounted for 19% of total sales. Volvo's earnings are expected to be up 6% this year and rise another 1% in FY24 at $1.72 per share.

Earnings estimate revisions have remained higher over the last 60 days. The EV growth of Volvo is very intriguing and the strong February numbers are starting to reaffirm that 2023 could be another stellar year for the company.
